## 9. Future Improvements

### Incremental Loading (Watermark Pattern)
Current pipeline does full refresh — reads all 9,986 rows every run. For daily-updating data, this is wasteful.

Implementation: Add a `watermark` config table storing `last_processed_timestamp`. Silver reads only Bronze rows where `ingested_at > last_watermark`. After successful run, update watermark. This changes pipeline from O(total rows) to O(new rows per day).

### SCD Type 2 on dim_customer
Current implementation overwrites customer attributes when they change (SCD Type 1). If a customer changes from Consumer to Corporate segment, the history is lost.

SCD Type 2 adds: `effective_date`, `expiry_date`, `is_current` columns. Old record gets expiry_date set. New record is inserted with current date as effective_date and is_current=true. Historical fact rows still point to the old record — preserving the state at time of transaction.

### Data Quarantine Layer
Currently 8 duplicate rows are silently dropped. In production, these should route to a quarantine Delta table with a rejection reason column. Data engineers review quarantined records to determine if they represent source system bugs that need fixing upstream.

### Real-Time Streaming
Current pipeline is batch — triggered manually or on schedule. Replace Bronze ingestion with Spark Structured Streaming reading from a message queue (Kafka, Event Hubs). Pipeline becomes event-driven, processing records within seconds of arrival.

### Great Expectations Integration
Replace custom Python assertion checks with Great Expectations framework. Provides standardized expectation definitions, automatic documentation of data contracts, and HTML quality reports that non-technical stakeholders can read.

